#compdef dome
# ============================================================================
#  _dome — dome: DOME Engine (Design-Oriented Minimalist Engine)
#          — a lightweight game development environment where
#          GAMES ARE WRITTEN IN WREN scripting language with
#          built-in SDL2 graphics/audio/input + a software
#          renderer (no shaders / no GPU dependencies) targeting
#          retro/pixel-art game development workflows
#          (Aviv "avivbeeri" Beeri — Australian game dev, DOME
#          creator)
#
#  Source-direct extraction from
#    https://github.com/domeengine/dome/blob/main/src/main.c
#      (hand-rolled C argv parser using strcmp for subcommands
#      and option flags)
#    https://github.com/wren-lang/wren-cli (wren_cli — the
#    canonical Wren interpreter binary; the underlying Wren
#    language implementation by Bob Nystrom)
#
#  Maintained by Aviv "avivbeeri" Beeri (Australian game dev,
#  DOME creator) and contributors.  domeengine/dome: 482 GH
#  stars (small but active community, used for indie game
#  jams + retro game development).  DOME is a Wren-scripted
#  game development environment focused on RETRO / PIXEL-ART /
#  LO-FI aesthetics — internal canvas is 320x240 (upscaled 2x
#  to 640x480 window by default), software-rendered (no shader
#  programming needed), with built-in SDL2 audio (256-tone
#  synthesizer + sample playback) and Gamepad/Keyboard/Mouse
#  input.  Games are written in WREN (Bob Nystrom's lightweight
#  scripting language) and packaged into a `.egg` archive that
#  DOME loads at runtime.  Companion tools: `dome embed`
#  (Wren-source-to-C-include for plugin development), `dome
#  fuse` (merge .egg bundle into the DOME binary for
#  standalone distribution), `dome nest` (bundle a project into
#  a single .egg file).  Sister tools: pico8 (Pico-8 fantasy
#  console — closest spiritual sibling; commercial, not in
#  corpus), tic80 (TIC-80 fantasy console — in corpus + STOCK
#  via _tic80), love2d (Lua game framework — in corpus via
#  _love), R436 lobster (Wouter van Oortmerssen's compiled
#  game-scripting; closest related corpus entry), wren_cli (IN
#  CORPUS via _wren_cli — the canonical Wren interpreter), godot
#  (in corpus + STOCK; GDScript), defold (commercial Lua engine).
#
#  CLI library taxonomy update: 1st Wren CLI library — DOME's
#  **HAND-ROLLED C STRCMP-CHAIN PARSER** in `src/main.c` (using
#  `STRINGS_EQUAL(a, b)` macro defined as `strcmp(a, b) == 0`).
#  Wren joins the cross-language taxonomy as the 40th
#  documented language.  🎉 NEW LANGUAGE entry — Wren joins
#  alongside Rust, Go, TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby, Perl,
#  Haskell, OCaml, Elixir, R, Bash, Deno, Lua, Scheme, Clojure,
#  Common Lisp, Racket, Crystal, Nim, Zig, Odin, V, Mojo, Roc,
#  Hare, Standard ML, Erlang, Pony, Prolog, Pike, F#, Janet,
#  D, Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster, Curry, Mercury.
#
#  WREN is a SMALL, FAST, CLASS-BASED CONCURRENT SCRIPTING
#  LANGUAGE designed by Bob "munificent" Nystrom (author of
#  CRAFTING INTERPRETERS — the seminal interpreter-design book
#  freely available at https://craftinginterpreters.com) and
#  released in 2014.  Distinctive features: SYNTAX inspired by
#  Lua + Smalltalk (lightweight closure syntax, named arguments
#  via method-call style); CLASSES with inheritance (single
#  inheritance + mixins via "foreign classes"); FIBERS for
#  cooperative concurrency (lightweight green threads with
#  yield/resume); REFERENCE COUNTING (no tracing GC; immediate
#  cleanup); EMBEDDED-FIRST DESIGN (small VM ~10KLOC C; embedded
#  in DOME, custom game engines, web tools, etc.); NO STANDARD
#  LIBRARY (the host application provides everything beyond
#  core language semantics — DOME provides graphics/audio/input,
#  wren_cli provides IO/process/stdin-stdout, etc.).  Use cases:
#  game development (DOME, FBX2glTF, indie engines), embedded
#  scripting (configuration languages, plugin systems), and
#  educational interpreter-design (Crafting Interpreters book
#  uses Wren-inspired examples).
#
#  DOME's argv parser is HAND-ROLLED — pure C `STRINGS_EQUAL(a,
#  b)` macro chains in `main()` to dispatch subcommands and
#  options.  No getopt(), no getopt_long(), no third-party
#  library.  Strategy:
#    #define STRINGS_EQUAL(a, b) (strcmp(a, b) == 0)
#
#    int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
#      // Iterate argv looking for known subcommand keywords
#      // and option flags via STRINGS_EQUAL chains
